					<dd class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
<div class="format_text" id="comment-body-1383">
<p>This article is silly, and reminds me of the Seinfeld episode where Jerry and Kramer are arguing over &#8220;write-offs,&#8221; and it quickly becomes obvious neither has any idea of what they&#8217;re talking about.</p>
<p>What this article is saying is that if you spend all of your business income you owe no tax. Well, of course. They can&#8217;t tax you on money you don&#8217;t have. (the IRA and 401k money isn&#8217;t spent, but it is out of reach; you cannot use it, so until you retire it can be considered as &#8220;spent.&#8221;)</p>
</div>
					</dd>
					<dt class="comment byuser comment-author-wbrounds bypostauthor odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="comment-1388">
<span class="avatar"><a href="http://www.howtovanish.com/" rel="nofollow"></a></span>
<span class="comment_num"><a href="#comment-1388" title="Permalink to this comment" rel="nofollow">2</a></span>
<span class="comment_author"><a href="http://www.howtovanish.com/"   rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Bill Rounds J.D.</a></span>
<span class="comment_time">April 29, 2011 at 2:09 pm</span>

					</dt>
					<dd class="comment byuser comment-author-wbrounds bypostauthor odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
<div class="format_text" id="comment-body-1388">
<p>You&#8217;re right.  You can either spend the money on direct, and often immediate, benefits to yourself and your family, or you can pay that money in taxes to have people molest you at the airport, search your cell phone records without a warrant, buy weapons for dictators around the world, and then spend more of your money to go blow those same weapons up.  Even though a wise investment in a self-directed IRA is not immediately available, I would hardly consider that money &#8220;spent.&#8221;  The net effect of a smart and disciplined person working as an independent contractor instead of an employee can be a significantly faster rate of wealth accumulation.</p>
</div>
					</dd>
					<dt class="comment even thread-even depth-1" id="comment-1811">
<span class="avatar"></span>
<span class="comment_num"><a href="#comment-1811" title="Permalink to this comment" rel="nofollow">3</a></span>
<span class="comment_author">JPM</span>
<span class="comment_time">December 25, 2011 at 11:35 pm</span>

					</dt>
					<dd class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
<div class="format_text" id="comment-body-1811">
<p>I recently read this piece via Lewrockwell.com. For years I have been promoting the idea that the employee/employer relationship died in the 80&#8242;s and that we would all benefit from moving to contractor-based employment as a standard in the US. </p>
<p>Two key issues with this:<br />
1. Employee/Employer relationship may be more expensive than a contractor due to the lack of wrap rates, but benefits corporations by removing the possibility of price wars for top talent</p>
<p>2. We cannot accomplish this until health plans are available to citizens in the way auto and life insurance plans are provided. Individual health care plans suck no matter how much you pay. Health care providers are in cahoots with large corporations to offer them the best plans allowing them to attract and retain the best talent for less than the market would pay in a contractor-based environment. </p>
<p>Most importantly, the employee/employer relationships benefits big government. It allows them to control the masses by controlling wages, benefits and the ability to have basic survival needs. Employer relationships allow invasive inspection of your background that you don&#8217;t have the right to know from a contractor, which in turn allows the government to control your ability to earn by what information is provided to companies in background checks.</p>
</div>
					</dd>
					<dt class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="comment-2101">
<span class="avatar"></span>
<span class="comment_num"><a href="#comment-2101" title="Permalink to this comment" rel="nofollow">4</a></span>
<span class="comment_author">Dick</span>
